  <static seed="1157" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/simplifyRationalExpressions170.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the following expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain on the simplified expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{6}-4x^{5}-5x^{4}}{x^{6}-x^{5}-20x^{4}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{x+1}{x+4}, x\ne 5\hbox{ and }x\ne 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cross out common factors:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{6}-4x^{5}-5x^{4}}{x^{6}-x^{5}-20x^{4}}} \amp = \frac{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}-4x-5\right)}}{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}-x-20\right)}} \\
                     \amp = \frac{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+1\right)}}{{x^{4}\mathopen{}\left(x-5\right)\mathopen{}\left(x+4\right)}} \\
                     \amp = {\frac{x+1}{x+4}, x\ne 5\hbox{ and }x\ne 0}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>x^{4}</m> and <m>x - 5</m> were crossed out, the domain conditions lost during the simplification are <m>x \ne 0</m> and <m>x \ne 5</m>.</p>
</solution>
